#We can see that the target classes are considerably imbalanced (Type_S > Normal > Type_H)
#The ML model will be biased towards the majority classes, classifying most of the patients as belonging to the majority classes
#Hence balanced datasets are preferred in machine learning
#Oversampling, Undersampling and Synthetic Data Creation (eg:SMOTE -Synthetic Minority Oversampling technique) are some ways to make the target classes balanced
  • Perform train-test split.
In [29]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=1)
  • Perform normalisation or scaling if required
In [30]:
#Since we are going to use KNN model which works based on distance, the data must be on same scale across all the predictors
#We are doing scaling after splitting the data into training and test sets.
#This is to prevent data leakage from test data to training data. The model should not have any knowledge of test data.
#Scaling can be done in multiple ways. Here we use StandardScaler from sklearn library.

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
sc = StandardScaler()
X_train_std = sc.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_std = sc.transform(X_test) #We apply fit only to training data and not test data so that scaling parameters are derived only from training data and are applied to test data as well

In [37]:
#Precision = True Positives/(True Positives+False Positives)
#Precision represents the proportion of true positive samples among all the samples classified as positive
#Recall = True Positives/(True Positives+False Negatives)
#Recall represents the proportion of samples correctly classified as positive among all the samples that are actually positive
#F1-score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall and is a key indicator of model's performance with imbalanced datasets.
#Accuracy is the ratio of number of correct predictions to the total number of predictions made. Accuracy is not a reliable metric for imbalanced datasets.
#Macro average calculates the average without considering the proportion of each class
#Weighted average calculates the average considering the proportion of each class
In [38]:
#In our case, as expected, we are seeing low recall and precision values for the minority classes (a consequence of imbalalnced datasets)
#The average values are also low as a result of poor classification of the 2 minority classes
#The precision and recall values are decent for the majority class (Type_S) as expected
  • Automate the task of finding best values of K for KNN.
In [39]:
training_accuracy = []
test_accuracy = []
# try n_neighbors from 1 to 50
neighbors_settings = range(1, 50)

for n_neighbors in neighbors_settings:
    # build the model
    clf = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=n_neighbors, weights='distance')
    clf.fit(X_train_std, y_train)
    # record training set accuracy
    training_accuracy.append(clf.score(X_train_std, y_train))
    # record generalization accuracy
    test_accuracy.append(clf.score(X_test_std, y_test))

plt.plot(neighbors_settings, training_accuracy, label="training accuracy")
plt.plot(neighbors_settings, test_accuracy, label="test accuracy")
plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
plt.xlabel("n_neighbors")
plt.legend()
plt.show()
print(np.where(test_accuracy == np.amax(test_accuracy))) #getting index of max test accuracy value in array. K value would be index+1
print(np.amax(test_accuracy)) #to display max test accuracy

In [41]:
#Using GridSearchCV to find optimal hyper-parameters for our model
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
knn = KNeighborsClassifier()
parameters_KNN = {
    'n_neighbors': list(range(1,50)),
    'leaf_size': list(range(1,5)), #Leaf size passed to BallTree or KDTree. This can affect the speed of the construction and query, as well as the memory required to store the tree.
    'weights': ('uniform', 'distance')} #uniform - all points in neighborhood are weighed equally; distance - weight is based on distance of neighbor
                   
grid_search_KNN = GridSearchCV(
    estimator=knn,
    param_grid=parameters_KNN,
    scoring = 'accuracy', #scoring metric
    n_jobs = -1, #to use all processor threads for neighbor search
    cv =50) #number of splits for cross validation
grid_search_KNN.fit(X, y)
print(grid_search_KNN.best_estimator_)
print(grid_search_KNN.best_score_)

KNeighborsClassifier(leaf_size=1, n_neighbors=24, weights='distance')
0.8619047619047621

Conclusion and improvisation:¶

Write your conclusion on the results.¶

  • The final best trained model classifies patients as belonging to Type_H or Type_S or Normal class with an accuracy of around 82% on test data
  • Out of the 93 patients in test data, our model has correctly classified 20 as Normal, 14 as Type_H and 42 as Type_S
  • 8 normal patients have been incorrectly classified. 4 as Type_H and 4 as Type_S
  • 3 Type_H patients have been incorrectly classified as Normal
  • 6 Type_S patients have been incorrectly classified. 4 as Normal and 2 as Type_H
  • The model has average precision and recall close to 80% with higher values for majority class Type_S and lower values for minority classes Type_H and Normal.
  • Oversampling, Undersampling and Synthetic Data Creation (eg:SMOTE -Synthetic Minority Oversampling technique) are some ways to make the target classes balanced
  • Through the box plots, it was observed that there is considerable overlap in few feature distributions between classes which affects classification accuracy of KNN model adversely
  • We were able to improve the accuracy score on test data by around 7% by optimizing the hyper-parameters using GridSearchCV
  • It might be possible to further improve the classification accuracy for the dataset by opting for other classification algorithms like Logistic Regression, Naive Bayes, Support Vector Machines etc. The other models will certainly be better for larger datasets where KNN becomes computationally expensive as it has to perform distance calculations for every new point.

Detailed suggestions or improvements or on quality, quantity, variety, velocity, veracity etc. on the data points¶

collected by the research team to perform a better data analysis in future.¶

  • A more balanced dataset would help in better predicting the classes as data imbalance leads to bias towards the majority class/classes.
  • Few of the features have significant distribution overlap between the classes. Features with no or minimal overlap will improve classification accuracy especially with KNN model
  • The values populated in 'Class' feature could have been more cosistent. (eg: multiple values like 'Type_S' & 'tp_s' are available in the feature that seem to denote the same class).
  • There are only 310 samples in the dataset. More number of samples will help better predict the classes. (even though it might get computationally expensive for KNN model)
  • More descriptive feature and class names instead of the short forms given in the dataset or explanations for the same would have helped in understanding the dataset better.
